The Gauss code for the trefoil knot (also known as the "treble clef" or "triple tie") is: 

`RAST`

To determine if this knot is equivalent to an unknot, we can create a diagram of its closure and analyze it using Reidemeister moves. Here's one possible representation of the trefoil knot in terms of a diagram with three crossings: 

```
       /\
      /  \
     /    \
    /______ \
   /        \/ \
  /_________| \
 /_____________| \
 |              | \
 |             / \
 |           /   \
 |          /___ \
 |         /     \
 |        /_/\_ \
 |       /       \
 |      /_______ \
 |     /_________|
```
 
If we draw a pushoff loop on each strand at the beginning and end of the crossing, then apply the first two Reidemeister moves to convert all but the middle strand into a full circle, we get: 

```
       /\
      /  \
     /    \
    /______ \
   /        \
  /_________|
 /_____________|
```
 
Applying the third move to eliminate the last double point yields: 

```
       /\
      /  \
     /    V
    /______ _
   /        |
  /_________|
 /_____________|
```
 
As you can see, the middle strand now forms a large circle, indicating that the knot has been reduced to a simple unlink (a link with no components). Therefore, the trefoil knot is not equivalent to the unknot. It contains a single non-trivial cycle which cannot be eliminated by any combination of Reidemeister moves.
